    pearls: ["JVD assessment requires correct patient positioning at 45 degrees -- if the patient is flat, even normal JVP may appear elevated; if sitting upright at 90 degrees, elevated JVP may be missed","The hepatojugular reflux test differentiates right heart failure from other causes of elevated JVP: only in heart failure does the right ventricle fail to accommodate the increased venous return, producing a sustained JVP rise","Kussmaul sign (JVP rising with inspiration instead of falling) is characteristic of constrictive pericarditis and cardiac tamponade -- normal inspiration should decrease intrathoracic pressure and increase venous return, lowering JVP","Beck triad (hypotension, JVD, muffled heart sounds) is the classic presentation of cardiac tamponade, but all three components are present in only 10-40% of cases; JVD may be absent in hypovolemic patients","In cardiac tamponade, do NOT give diuretics or nitroglycerin -- these reduce preload, which is the only mechanism maintaining cardiac output against pericardial compression; treatment is emergent pericardiocentesis","Tension pneumothorax causes JVD by compressing mediastinal structures and obstructing venous return -- immediate needle decompression is lifesaving; do NOT wait for chest X-ray confirmation"],
