    pearls: ["Cannon a waves are pathognomonic for AV dissociation -- the atrium contracts against a closed tricuspid valve, producing a tall venous pressure wave; look for irregular cannon waves in complete heart block and regular cannon waves in junctional rhythm","Absent a waves + irregularly irregular JVP = atrial fibrillation; the loss of organized atrial contraction eliminates the a wave component from the venous waveform","In cardiac tamponade, the x descent is preserved (ventricular systole still pulls the atrial floor down) but the y descent is absent (pericardial pressure prevents passive diastolic filling) -- this pattern distinguishes tamponade from constrictive pericarditis","In constrictive pericarditis, the y descent is prominent and steep (Friedreich sign) because early diastolic filling is rapid until the non-compliant pericardium abruptly limits further expansion","Right ventricular infarction presents with elevated JVP, clear lung fields, and hypotension -- treat with IV fluid bolus (preload dependent); do NOT give nitroglycerin or diuretics as these reduce preload and can cause cardiovascular collapse","Giant cv waves from tricuspid regurgitation can be so prominent that they cause visible pulsation of the earlobes -- this physical finding, when present, is highly specific for severe TR"],
